         b'\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t<article id="post-848" class="post-848 post type-pos'
         b't status-publish format-standard hentry category-agile category-deci'
         b'sion-analysis category-requirements-risks category-talk">\n\t\t<hea'
         b'der class="entry-header">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<h1 class="entry-title"><a h'
         b'ref="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/the-value-of-requirements-uncertaint'
         b'y/" title="Permalink to The Value of Requirements Uncertainty" rel="'
         b'bookmark">The Value of Requirements Uncertainty</a></h1>\n\t\t\t'
         b'\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-meta">\n\t\t\t\t<span class="sep">Po'
         b'sted on </span><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/the-value-of-requ'
         b'irements-uncertainty/" title="8:39 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="e'
         b'ntry-date" datetime="2013-10-20T20:39:50+00:00" pubdate>October 20, '
         b'2013</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span'
         b'> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://letier'
         b'.cs.ucl.ac.uk/author/ucaceyl/" title="View all posts by Emmanuel" re'
         b'l="author">Emmanuel</a></span></span>\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-meta -'
         b'->\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t</header><!-- .entry-header -->\n\n\t\t\t\t<di'
         b'v class="entry-content">\n\t\t\t<p><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.'
         b'uk/the-value-of-requirements-uncertainty/10d67249/" rel="attachment '
         b'wp-att-851"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-851" title="A'
         b'xel" src="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/10d67249.jpg'
         b'" alt="Axel" width="3872" height="2592" /></a>On 4 October, I partic'
         b'ipated to <a href="http://icampus.grascomp.be/courses/COMP055/">an e'
         b'vent in honour of Axel van Lamsweerde</a>, my former PhD supervisor,'
         b' who turned emeritus this fall. The event had an impressive list of '
         b'speakers and generated many interesting discussions in and around th'
         b'e warm auditorium SUD11, a lecture room I have spent hours in as a s'
         b'tudent years ago.</p>\n<p>I talked about the value of requirement'
         b's uncertainty. I made the point that uncertainty is inevitable in re'
         b'quirements and architecture decisions and we should therefore embrac'
         b'e uncertainty instead of ignoring it. I argued that our past focus o'
         b'n precise specification is misguided when requirements are uncertain'
         b' and called for a goal-based scientific approach to software decisio'
         b'ns under uncertainty. Important and fascinating research lies ahead '
         b'of us.</p>\n<p>The slides are on my new <a href="http://www.slide'
         b'share.net/EmmanuelLetier/" target="_blank">slideshare </a>account an'
         b'd here:<br />\n<iframe src="//www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_'
         b'code/key/31lBj8JEfnbRvt" width="425" height="355" frameborder="0" ma'
         b'rginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no" style="border:1px soli'
         b'd #CCC; border-width:1px; margin-bottom:5px; max-width: 100%;" allow'
         b'fullscreen> </iframe> </p>\n<p><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.u'
         b'k/the-value-of-requirements-uncertainty/emeritat-lectures-axel-van-l'
         b'amsweerde4-oct-2013/" rel="attachment wp-att-854"><img class="alignc'
         b'enter size-full wp-image-854" title="A Call to Action" src="http://l'
         b'etier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/x100_07538.jpg" alt="A Call to'
         b' Action" width="4288" height="2848" /></a></p>\n\t\t\t\t\t</div><!'
         b'-- .entry-content -->\n\t\t\n\t\t<footer class="entry-meta">\n\t'
         b'\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="cat-links">\n\t\t\t\t<span class='
         b'"entry-utility-prep entry-utility-prep-cat-links">Posted in</span> <'
         b'a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/category/agile/" title="View all '
         b'posts in Agile" rel="category tag">Agile</a>, <a href="http://letier'
         b'.cs.ucl.ac.uk/category/decision-analysis/" title="View all posts in '
         b'Decision Analysis" rel="category tag">Decision Analysis</a>, <a href'
         b'="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/category/requirements-risks/" title="Vi'
         b'ew all posts in Requirements Risks" rel="category tag">Requirements '
         b'Risks</a>, <a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/category/talk/" title'
         b'="View all posts in Talk" rel="category tag">Talk</a>\t\t\t</span>\n'
         b'\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t</footer><!-- #entry-meta -->'
         b'\n\t</article><!-- #post-848 -->\n\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t<article'
         b' id="post-668" class="post-668 post type-post status-publish format-'
         b'standard hentry category-goal-modelling-2 category-requirements-risk'
         b's">\n\t\t<header class="entry-header">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<h1 class="ent'
         b'ry-title"><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/incomplete-obstacle-re'
         b'solution-in-patient-monitoring-system/" title="Permalink to Incomple'
         b'te Obstacle Resolution in Patient Monitoring System" rel="bookmark">'
         b'Incomplete Obstacle Resolution in Patient Monitoring System</a></h1>'
         b'\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-meta">\n\t\t\t\t<span class='
         b'"sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/incomplet'
         b'e-obstacle-resolution-in-patient-monitoring-system/" title="9:39 pm"'
         b' rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2012-05-31T21:39:'
         b'23+00:00" pubdate>May 31, 2012</time></a><span class="by-author"> <s'
         b'pan class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url'
         b' fn n" href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/author/ucaceyl/" title="View'
         b' all posts by Emmanuel" rel="author">Emmanuel</a></span></span>\t'
         b'\t\t</div><!-- .entry-meta -->\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t</header><!-- .ent'
         b'ry-header -->\n\n\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-content">\n\t\t\t<p>Pat'
         b'ient monitoring is <a href="http://domino.watson.ibm.com/tchjr/journ'
         b'alindex.nsf/0/751ad3c1867f587a85256bfa00685aaa?OpenDocument">one of '
         b'the oldest case studies</a> in software engineering and it has been '
         b'used extensively to illustrate a variety of modelling and analysis t'
         b'echniques. Yet, incidents with patient monitoring systems still happ'
         b'en and we can still learn by looking at them.</p>\n<p>This story '
         b'was reported on <a href="http://catless.ncl.ac.uk/Risks/26.86.html#s'
         b'ubj1">the RISK forum</a> this week.</p>\n<blockquote><p><strong>P'
         b'atient Died at New York VA Hospital After Alarm Was Ignored</strong>'
         b'</p>\n<p>Charles Ornstein and Tracy Weber, ProPublica, 15 May 201'
         b'2</p>\n<p>Registered nurses at a Manhattan Veterans Affairs hospi'
         b'tal failed to notice a patient had become disconnected from a cardia'
         b'c monitor until after his heart had stopped and he could not be revi'
         b'ved, according to a report Monday from the VA inspector general.</p>'
         b'\n<p>The incident from last June was the second such death at the'
         b' hospital involving a patient connected to a monitor in a six-month '
         b'period. The first, along with two earlier deaths at a Denver VA hosp'
         b'ital, raised questions about nursing competency in the VA system, Pr'
         b'oPublica reported last month.</p>\n<p>The deaths also prompted a '
         b'broader review of skills and training of VA nurses. Only half of 29 '
         b'VA facilities surveyed by the inspector general in a recent report h'
         b'ad adequately documented that their nurses had skills to perform the'
         b'ir duties. Even though some nurses &#8220;did not demonstrate compet'
         b'ency in one or more required skills,&#8221; the government report st'
         b'ated, there was no evidence of retraining. &#8230;</p>\n<p><a hre'
         b'f="http://www.propublica.org/article/patient-died-at-new-york-va-hos'
         b'pital-after-alarm-was-ignored">http://www.propublica.org/article/pat'
         b'ient-died-at-new-york-va-hospital-after-alarm-was-ignored</a></p></b'
         b'lockquote>\n<p>So it seems to be the nurses&#8217; fault and the '
         b'solution to prevent this from happening again is better nurse traini'
         b'ng. But is this the only way to look at this problem? Blaming the op'
         b'erator is a common reaction when this sort of incidents occur, but v'
         b'ery often the operator\xe2\x80\x99s error is caused or made more '
         b'likely by poor decisions in the system design.</p>\n<p>Being curi'
         b'ous, I\xe2\x80\x99ve had a quick look at the <a href="http://www.'
         b'propublica.org/documents/item/356534-vaoig-nyc1.html">more detailed '
         b'report</a> on these incidents, and this is how it describes the diff'
         b'erent kinds of\xc2\xa0 alarm in this system:</p>\n<blockquote><p>Th'
         b'e telemetry monitoring equipment at the system triggers three types '
         b'of audible alarms:</p></blockquote>\n<blockquote><p><strong>- Red'
         b' Alarm </strong>is an audible critical alarm that is loud and contin'
         b'uous. It indicates the need to immediately check on a patien'
         b't\xe2\x80\x99s status and vital signs.<strong></strong></p></bloc'
         b'kquote>\n<blockquote><p><strong>- Y</strong><strong>ellow Alarm <'
         b'/strong>is a quieter and intermittent audible alarm that stops after'
         b' several minutes. It indicates a temporary irregularity in the heart'
         b' rate or rhythm that is not immediately critical.<strong></strong></'
         b'p></blockquote>\n<blockquote><p><strong>- Blue Alarm </strong>is '
         b'similar to the yellow alarm and indicates a problem with the system '
         b'itself or an improperly connected, or disconnected, telemetry lead.<'
         b'/p></blockquote>\n<p>I\xe2\x80\x99m sure you all see what the prob'
         b'lem might have been; having similar alarms for possibly critical and'
         b' non-critical events is probably not a good idea.</p>\n<p>This in'
         b'cident provides a good example to illustrate the technique of<a href'
         b'="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.letier/publications/TSE-Obstacles.'
         b'pdf"> goal-oriented obstacle analysis</a>.</p>\n<p>An obstacle is'
         b' something that could go wrong and prevent a system from satisfying '
         b'its goals. Here, the system designers had identified that the obstac'
         b'le &#8220;Patient is accidentally disconnected from the monitor&#822'
         b'1; would obstruct the goal &#8220;Maintain Accurate Measures of Pati'
         b'ent Vital Signs&#8221; which itself contribute, along many other goa'
         b'ls, to the goal &#8220;Keep Patient Alive&#8221;. The resolution of '
         b'that obstacle was to include an alarm to warn the nurses when this h'
         b'appens (technically, in our framework we would call this an obstacle'
         b' mitigation).</p>\n<p>Unfortunately, they may not have paid enoug'
         b'h attention to the goal that this obstacle resolution was meant to a'
         b'chieve. The goal is not just to send an alarm when the patient gets '
         b'disconnected (which technically, in our jargon, we would call a weak'
         b' mitigation), it is to get the nurses to react, reconnect the patien'
         b't and keep him alive (what we would call a strong mitigation). To ac'
         b'hieve this latter goal, the system relies on the assumption that nur'
         b'ses will react to the disconnection alarm. This assumption itself ha'
         b's an obstacle \xe2\x80\x9cNurse Does Not React to Disconnection A'
         b'larm\xe2\x80\x9d, which is even more likely to happen if the crit'
         b'ical disconnection alarm is similar to another non-critical alarm. I'
         b't is this obstacle that probably had not received sufficient attenti'
         b'on or wasn&#8217;t even considered during the system design and led '
         b'to the incidents. The resolution that is being proposed now is \xe2'
         b'\x80\x9cGive the nurses better training\xe2\x80\x9d (an instance of'
         b' obstacle reduction in our framework). But an alternative resolution'
         b', that could have been chosen at design time, would of course have b'
         b'een to make the &#8220;blue alarm&#8221; signalling an instrument ma'
         b'lfunction sound similar to the critical &#8220;red alarm&#8221; rath'
         b'er than to the non-critical yellow one.</p>\n<p>The techniques of'
         b' goal-oriented obstacle analysis provides a modelling and analysis f'
         b'ramework to carry out this kind of reasoning in a systematic and rig'
         b'orous way. You can check <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.le'
         b'tier/publications/TSE-Obstacles.pdf">the paper </a>for details.<'
         b'/p>\n\t\t\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-content -->\n\t\t\n\t\t<footer clas'
         b's="entry-meta">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="cat-links">'
         b'\n\t\t\t\t<span class="entry-utility-prep entry-utility-prep-cat-'
         b'links">Posted in</span> <a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/category'
         b'/goal-modelling-2/" title="View all posts in Goal Modelling" rel="ca'
         b'tegory tag">Goal Modelling</a>, <a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/'
         b'category/requirements-risks/" title="View all posts in Requirements '
         b'Risks" rel="category tag">Requirements Risks</a>\t\t\t</span>\n\t'
         b'\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t</footer><!-- #entry-meta -->\n'
         b'\t</article><!-- #post-668 -->\n\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t<article '
         b'id="post-621" class="post-621 post type-post status-publish format-s'
         b'tandard hentry category-publication category-requirements-risks cate'
         b'gory-system-evolution">\n\t\t<header class="entry-header">\n\t\t\t\t'
         b'\t\t<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/re'
         b'quirements-are-never-perfect-when-are-they-good-enough/" title="Perm'
         b'alink to Requirements are never perfect. When are they good enough?"'
         b' rel="bookmark">Requirements are never perfect. When are they good e'
         b'nough?</a></h1>\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-meta">\n\t'
         b'\t\t\t<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://letier.cs.'
         b'ucl.ac.uk/requirements-are-never-perfect-when-are-they-good-enough/"'
         b' title="9:16 am" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2'
         b'012-05-30T09:16:00+00:00" pubdate>May 30, 2012</time></a><span class'
         b'="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcar'
         b'd"><a class="url fn n" href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/author/ucace'
         b'yl/" title="View all posts by Emmanuel" rel="author">Emmanuel</a></s'
         b'pan></span>\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-meta -->\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t</'
         b'header><!-- .entry-header -->\n\n\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-content'
         b'">\n\t\t\t<p>We know it\xe2\x80\x99s impossible to write perfect '
         b'requirements. Requirements for complex systems will always be incomp'
         b'lete, contain defects such as ambiguities and inconsistencies, and f'
         b'ail to anticipate all changes that will happen during and after deve'
         b'lopment. This creates <em>requirements risks</em> \xe2\x80\x93 th'
         b'e risks of developing wrong requirements. Good requirements engineer'
         b'ing can limit these risks but they can never be entirely eliminated.'
         b' Requirements must therefore be <em>good enough</em> so that the rem'
         b'aining risks are acceptable to the project.</p>\n<p>But how do we'
         b' decide when the requirements are good enough and their risks accept'
         b'able?</p>\n<p>In our paper on \xe2\x80\x9c<a href="http://www.spri'
         b'ngerlink.com/content/n542231108g17114/">Early Failure Predictions in'
         b' Feature Request Management Systems</a>\xe2\x80\x9d, we\xe2\x80'
         b'\x99ve experimented with one approach to address this question. The'
         b' context for this experiment are large-scale open source projects, s'
         b'uch as Firefox, Thunderbird and four others, where features are regu'
         b'larly added, modified, and removed \xc2\xa0in response to stakehol'
         b'ders\xe2\x80\x99 change requests that are submitted and discussed'
         b' online. Our idea was to apply machine learning on past change reque'
         b'sts to build predictive models that would give early warnings of ris'
         b'ks associated to new change requests. Camilo Fitzgerald, the lead au'
         b'thor of the paper, has developed an automated technique that gives e'
         b'arly warnings about the following risks:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pr'
         b'oduct failure</strong>: the risk that there will be bug reports or c'
         b'hange requests associated with the implementation of a change reques'
         b't;</li>\n<li><strong>Abandoned development</strong>: the risk tha'
         b't the implementation of a change request will be abandoned before co'
         b'mpletion;</li>\n<li><strong>Late development</strong>: the risk t'
         b'hat the implementation of a change request will not be completed in '
         b'time;</li>\n<li><strong>Removed Feature</strong>: the risk that t'
         b'he implementation of a change request will have to be removed from t'
         b'he product (typically because it conflicts with other features or re'
         b'quirements);</li>\n<li><strong>Rejection Reversal</strong>: the r'
         b'isk that a decision to reject a change request is premature and will'
         b' have to be reverted.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The risk warnings are genera'
         b'ted by analysing a series of simple characteristics in the discussio'
         b'n associated with the change requests such as the number of persons '
         b'who participated in the discussion, the length of the discussion, an'
         b'd an analysis of the words being used.</p>\n<p>The predictive mod'
         b'el is coupled with a simple model of the likely cost and benefit of '
         b'performing additional requirements analysis on a change request befo'
         b're its implementation. The model takes into account the relative cos'
         b't of additional requirements analysis with respect to the cost of th'
         b'e failure associated to the risk, and the probability that such addi'
         b'tional requirements analysis is actually successful at preventing fa'
         b'ilure (currently, these factors are estimated based on general empir'
         b'ical data and best judgement rather than calibrated with project-spe'
         b'cific data). This cost-benefit model is used for deciding the thresh'
         b'old at which to generate the risks warnings and recommend that furth'
         b'er requirements analysis take place on a change request before decid'
         b'ing on its implementation or not.</p>\n<p>The results of this exp'
         b'eriment are promising; they show that the approach is effective at d'
         b'iscovering which change requests have the highest risks of failure l'
         b'ater on in development. This information can be useful for project m'
         b'anagers and requirements engineers to decide whether more analysis i'
         b's needed on a change request before assigning it for implementation,'
         b' and to monitor the development of changes requests that have the hi'
         b'ghest risks more carefully.</p>\n<p>But this was really a first s'
         b'tep. Accuracy of the risk warnings might be improved in several ways'
         b', for example by applying more sophisticated natural language techni'
         b'ques for automatically detecting ambiguities in change requests, or '
         b'by taking into account characteristics of the software components af'
         b'fected by a change request. These improvements might also give us be'
         b'tter explanations about <em>why</em> a change request has a specific'
         b' risk. One of the biggest limitations of our current technique is th'
         b'at it identifies correlations between change requests and failure, b'
         b'ut it does not give us useful explanations about why some change req'
         b'uest characteristics lead to a certain type of failures. Much better'
         b' models will be needed for this approach to be really useful.</p'
         b'>\n<p>It would also be interesting to try this approach in other '
         b'contexts than online change request management systems.</p>\n<p>I'
         b't could for example be applied to traditional<strong> requirements d'
         b'ocuments. </strong>All we need is to be able to relate individual re'
         b'quirements items to their outcomes (e.g. how long they take to imple'
         b'ment, whether they have associated bug reports and change requests, '
         b'etc.) and we would be able to apply the same machine learning techni'
         b'ques to construct similar predictive models.</p>\n<p>It would als'
         b'o be interesting to apply it in the context of <strong>agile develop'
         b'ment</strong>. In this context, the approach could be viewed as a fo'
         b'rm of extensive automated retrospective analysis.\xc2\xa0 It would'
         b' consists in automatically analyzing all data and meta-data associat'
         b'ed with epics, users stories, acceptance tests, and their outcomes t'
         b'o try to learn characteristics of good and bad user stories with res'
         b'pect to requirements risks.</p>\n<p>The long term objective of th'
         b'is work is to make requirements risks much more visible and central '
         b'to software development than they are today. Instead of viewing requ'
         b'irements primarily as documentation, we should give more importance '
         b'their role as risk mitigation tools, and develop the techniques that'
         b' treat them as such.</p>\n<p>Note: A preprint of the paper is ava'
         b'ilable below and on my publication page</p>\n<ul>\n<li>C. Fitzgera'
         b'ld, E. Letier and A. Finkelstein, <a title="paper\'s preprint" hr'
         b'ef="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.letier/publications/2012-early_f'
         b'ailure_prediction-REJ-preprint.pdf">Early Failure Prediction in Feat'
         b'ure Request Management Systems: an Extended Study</a>, Requirements '
         b'Engineering Journal, Special Issue: RE&#8217;11 Best Papers, 2012.</'
         b'li>\n</ul>\n\t\t\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-content -->\n\t\t\n\t\t<f'
